label.value: Gas Chromatography and Flame Ionization Detection

value.value: A method that combines a flame ionization detector with a gas chromatograph to identify and quantify organic species within a gas stream.

A type of solid-phase immunoassay that uses distinctly colored microbeads coated with one or more reagents, which may be antigens, antibodies, oligonucleotides, enzyme substrates, or receptors, for the simultaneous detection and measurement of one or many analytes within a single sample.
A form of MRI in which a phase shift between flowing tissue and static tissue is generated in order to determine the quantity and velocity of blood flow.

A process by which the individual genomes of most or all of an entire population of a species undergoes a large-scale comparison of the DNA sequences within that population, using probabilistic matching tools. Such comparison allows for the study of microevolution within a population.

A type of complement receptor-dependent immune complex assay that uses Raji cells washed with anti-IgA, anti-IgG, anti-IgM, and anti-Ig (A+G+M) conjugated with an enzyme to detect the presence of circulating immune complexes in biologic fluids.
A type of complement receptor-dependent immune complex assay that uses radiolabeled anti-IgA, anti-IgG, or anti-IgM Raji cells to detect the presence of soluble immune complexes in biologic fluids.

An assessment of the cellular differentiation of a tumor as per the American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) tumor grading scale.

A score originally developed by Solez et al. (1993), and assigned based on the histologic evaluation of kidney allograft biopsies and the Banff Working Classification from the Banff Foundation for Allograft Pathology.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of arteriolar hyaline thickening present in a sample.
The histologic evaluation and diagnosis of the type of renal allograft rejection based on kidney biopsies and the Banff Working Classification from the Banff Foundation for Allograft Pathology.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of glomerulitis present in a sample.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of glomerulopathy present in a sample.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of intimal arteritis present in a sample.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of interstitial fibrosis present in a sample.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of mononuclear cell interstitial inflammation present in a sample.

An evaluation of the presence or degree of mitotic figures present in a sample.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of mesangial matrix present in a sample.

label.value: Platelet Endothelial Cell Adhesion Molecule 1 Measurement

value.value: The determination of the amount of platelet endothelial cell adhesion molecule 1 in a biological sample.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of peritubular capillaritis present in a sample.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of tubular atrophy present in a sample.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of tubulitis present in a sample.
An evaluation of the presence or degree of vascular fibrous intimal thickening present in a sample.
An indication as to whether disease is present in the bone marrow.
An assessment of the clinical performance, as measured by a rating or scale, as a condition of disease response to therapy.
An assessment of the disease response to therapy within the involved liver.

An assessment of the response to the therapy of the non-target enhancing lesion.
An assessment of the response to the therapy of the non-target non-enhancing lesion.
An assessment of the disease response to therapy within the involved spleen.
An assessment of steroid usage as a condition of disease response to therapy.
The determination of the level of gene transcription in a biological specimen. (CDISC)
The determination of the sequence of nucleotide residues along a genetic sub-region of interest.
The determination of the anticipated or extrapolated frequency of a single nucleotide polymorphism within a single interbreeding population.
The determination of the number of base pairs that compose a nucleotide sequence.
The determination of the location on a nucleotide sequence that is considered to be the beginning of a genetic region of interest.
The concentration that occurs at the midpoint time between dosing time and Tmax. (CDISC)

The ratio of free drug concentration to the total concentration.
The midpoint time between dosing time and Tmax. (CDISC)

The interval of time covered by the data points used in the terminal disposition phase regression analysis, divided by half life; this yields the terminal disposition phase duration expressed as the number of half lives. (CDISC)
A measure of the resistance of a system to expand, i.e. the pressure change that is required to elicit a unit volume change in the lungs; elastance is the reciprocal of compliance.
The greatest amount of pressure that can be generated by exhaling against a mouthpiece, which is a measure of the strength of respiratory muscles.

The greatest amount of pressure that can be generated by exhaling against a mouthpiece, which is a measure of the strength of respiratory muscles expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
The greatest amount of pressure that can be generated during inhalation against a fully occluded airway, which is used to measure the strength of respiratory muscles.

The greatest amount of pressure that can be generated during inhalation against a fully occluded airway, which is used to measure the strength of respiratory muscles expressed as a proportion of the predicted normal value.
The maximum rate of air flow expelled through the mouth, endotracheal, or tracheostomy tube during a cough.
An evaluation of the perfusion of a specific lung segment.
